Netflix Data

1. Download the netflix_titles at this link. Create a century variable taking two values:

- '21' if the released_year is greater or equal to 2000, and

- '20' otherwise. 
library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
library(tidytext)
## Warning: package 'tidytext' was built under R version 4.2.2
library(knitr)
df <- readr::read_csv('netflix_titles.csv')
df$century <-case_when(df$release_year >= 2000 ~ 21, df$release_year < 2000 ~ 20)

2. Word Frequency

  1. Convert the description to tokens, remove all the stop words. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 20th century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words.
df %>% filter(century==20) %>% select(title, description) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% head(1) %>%
  kable()

df %>% filter(century == 20) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  head(10) %>%

  1. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 21st century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words. Plot a side-by-side bar charts to compare the most frequent words by the two centuries.
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(type, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(type) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder_within(word, by = n, within = type)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = type)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~type, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Contribution to sentiment",
       y = NULL)+
  scale_y_reordered()

  1. Plot the word cloud of the words in the descriptions in the movies/TV Shows in the 20th century.
library(wordcloud) 
library(tidytext)

  1. Plot the word cloud of the words in the descriptions in the movies/TV Shows in the 21st century.
df %>% filter(century == 21) %>% 
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(type, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(type) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(type) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(sentiment, n, fill=type))+geom_col(position = 'fill')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

4. Sentiment Analysis

  1. Is movies/TV Shows in the 21st century tends to be more positive than those in 20th century? Use the sentiment analysis by Bing lexicons to address the question.
df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%

    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>%

5. Modeling

  1. Use the description to predict if a movie/TV show is in 20th or 21st century. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table.
library(caret)
library(themis)
## Warning: package 'themis' was built under R version 4.2.2
library(textrecipes)
## Warning: package 'textrecipes' was built under R version 4.2.2
library(yardstick)
## Warning: package 'yardstick' was built under R version 4.2.2
# Select data and set target 
df <- df %>% 
  mutate(target = type) %>% 
  select(target, description) 

# Convert text data to numeric variables
a <- recipe(target~description,
       data = df) %>% 
  step_tokenize(description) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df <- juice(a)

# Using Caret for modeling
set.seed(2021)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df$target, p = .07, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df[-splitIndex,]

forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                        method = "ranger")

pred <- predict(forest_ranger, df_test)

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
## Accuracy 
##   0.7049
  1. Create variable century2 taking three following values. (Hint: You can use the case_when function to do this)
- `21` if released_year is greater or equal to 2000

- `second_half_20`if released_year is greater than or equal to 1950 and less than 2000

- `first_half_20` otherwise
df <- readr::read_csv('netflix_titles.csv')

df$century2 <- case_when(df$release_year >= 2000 ~ "21", df$release_year >= 1950 ~ "second_half_20" , df$release_year>= 1900~"first_half_20")

Predict century2 using the descriptions. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table. (Notice that the codes for 8 should still work for this question)

  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df <- juice(a)

# Using Caret for modeling
set.seed(2022)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df$target, p = .01, 
                                  list = FALSE)

df_test <- df[-splitIndex,]

                        method = "ranger")

df <- readr::read_csv('netflix_titles.csv')
df$country1 <- case_when(df$country == "United States" ~"USA Movie", TRUE ~ "non USA Movie")
- Plot side-by-side word frequency by different categories of the newly created variable

library(caret)
library(themis)
library(textrecipes)
library(yardstick)
df2 <- read_tsv("user_reviews.tsv")
df2$rating <- case_when(df2$grade >= 7 ~ "good", TRUE ~ "bad")
set.seed(2021)

df2 <- df2 %>% 
  mutate(target = rating) %>% 
  select(target, text) 

# Convert text data to numeric variables
a <- recipe(target~text,
       data = df2) %>% 
  step_tokenize(text) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(text, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(text) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df2 <- juice(a)

splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df2$target, p = .1, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df2[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df2[-splitIndex,]

forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                        method = "ranger")

pred <- predict(forest_ranger, df_test)

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.7951843
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df_test$target)
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot
